Link: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/nelgiriyewithana/countries-of-the-world-2023

About: This dataset highlights global variations across countries, covering aspects such as demographics, economic performance, environmental conditions, healthcare, education, and other key indicators. It provides a broad overview of worldwide differences and trends.

Descriptions of variables:

country – name of the country

birth_rate – number of births per 1,000 people per year

life_expectancy – average number of years a person is expected to live

gdp – total economic output of the country

physicians_per_thousand – number of physicians per 1,000 people

maternal_mortality_ratio – number of maternal deaths per 100,000 live births

Data types:

country – qualitative, nominal

birth_rate – quantitative, continuous

life_expectancy – quantitative, continuous

gdp – quantitative, continuous

physicians_per_thousand – quantitative, continuous

maternal_mortality_ratio – quantitative, continuous

Motivation: I enjoy geography and wanted to compare countries to get a better understanding on how countries differ.

Summary:

Birth Rate and Life Expectancy: A strong negative correlation exists between birth rate and life expectancy, indicating that countries with higher birth rates tend to have lower life expectancies. Linear regression shows that for each increase in birth rate, life expectancy decreases by about 0.66 years.

GDP and Life Expectancy: Wealthier countries (high GDP) generally have higher life expectancies. A t-test shows a significant difference between life expectancy in high and low GDP countries, with high GDP countries having a mean life expectancy of 78.88 years compared to 71.66 years for low GDP countries.

GDP and Birth Rate: High GDP countries have significantly lower birth rates compared to low GDP countries, which is confirmed by another t-test. Higher GDP countries have a mean birth rate of 11.56, while low GDP countries have a mean of 21.02.

Relationship Between Birth Rate and Life Expectancy

#scatter plot w regression line
ggplot(global, aes(x = Birth_Rate, y = Life_expectancy)) +
  geom_point(color = "pink") +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", color = "black") +  #linear regression line
  labs(title = "Life Expectancy vs Birth Rate", 
       x = "Birth Rate", 
       y = "Life Expectancy") +
  theme_minimal()

Life Expectancy by GDP Group

data manipulation

#cleans the GDP and convert to numeric 
global <- global %>%
  mutate(GDP_numeric = as.numeric(gsub("[\\$,]", "", GDP))) ##remove dollar signs and commas

#data manipulation
#create a new variable to classify countries into low or high gdp based on gdp_numeric
global <- global %>%
  mutate(GDP_category = ifelse(GDP_numeric < 1000000000000, "Low GDP", "High GDP"))

#boxplot
ggplot(global, aes(x = GDP_category, y = Life_expectancy, fill = GDP_category)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("Low GDP" = "white", "High GDP" = "pink")) +  # Custom colors
  labs(title = "Life Expectancy Comparison: Low vs High GDP Countries",
       x = "GDP Category",
       y = "Life Expectancy") +
  theme_minimal()
## Warning: Removed 8 rows containing non-finite outside the scale range
## (`stat_boxplot()`).

#t-test
t_test_result <- t.test(Life_expectancy ~ GDP_category, data = global)
print(t_test_result)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  Life_expectancy by GDP_category
## t = 5.504, df = 22.552, p-value = 1.442e-05
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means between group High GDP and group Low GDP is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  4.502938 9.935586
## sample estimates:
## mean in group High GDP  mean in group Low GDP 
##               78.88125               71.66199
#p-value is much smaller than the significance level (0.05), indicating there's a significant difference between the life expectancy in high and low GDP countries

Conclusion: Life expectancy is closely associated with both GDP and birth rate. Wealthier countries tend to have higher GDP, longer life expectancies, and lower birth rates. In contrast, countries with lower GDP often experience shorter life expectancies and higher birth rates. This trend suggests that wealthier nations provide better living conditions, healthcare, and more controlled population growth, contributing to longer lifespans. However, it’s important to note that this is a correlation, not a causal relationship, and other factors may also influence these outcomes.
